Not as good as I thought it would be. I've looked at this boulder extensively over the years, and because it has some awesome features i figured it would easily be the best climb of the area. I mean its good, but you know what i really want. 

The big jugs are too sharp to be comfortable, the start was not as intuitive (I may have started low...), and the top was a little awk. 

It is forever in the shade so, thats a big plus, and it still looks cool. If you are in the area it is still a must do, but like an over-hyped movie, i had my hopes too high.

This version starts on the obvious seam with a high left heel, gets the cool left hand face crimp then locks up right hand to a good enough hold just below the lip. Hard not to dab but fun!

Gregor "grease gun" Recian-God, patiently waited his turn before splooshing all over this one. That high seam was way worse than i thought it would be and i left it worse than that even. I bet you cant even imagine. I cant and i was THERE. Sorry folks. I might be the sole reason drew doesn't have SteelFingersV8Soft. 

That high seam seems like it would be better and that nub nabbles like a champ. #alliteration #homophone

I have two shout outs:
#1 Marina for saying goodbye to rational thought and hello to simply sending shit!! When you get past the crux all that matters is sending, way to go! I was 10 billion percent (reference anyone?) sure that you would not fall.
#2 SteelFingersv8Soft - You bring smiles to many and I hope you have a nice winter season. You are a real hero and deserve a nice warm hearth to roast chestnuts at. If I hear you spent the winter alone I will drive out and warm you myself. Cheers.

ascents.comment:
Is this still V8 after Gregor 'Grease Gun" Recian-God gets on it? I rocketed off that hold so many times and even Shirley "This thing is so easy" Girth was having a hard time. Im so greasy even Marina had to admit to my insurmountable power of slip.  

Hardest thing I tried all trip by far. I had to throw a very high right heel as early as possible to take as much weight off my hands as possible since shoes don't sweat. Hands do. 

That being said, this boulder really is a nice boulder. So glad I didn't have to admit that Nate-Bro is stronger than me today.

ascents.comment: Definitely an area must do! Nothing too hard at the waterfall so it was nice to try rather hard on this one. Eileen and Chel (and Princess Ella - who loves my crash pad shade) ran out here with me for a quick sesh before a long sesh of drinking wine, beer, sake and meads!  Started on a low right hand crimp and a higher left hand side pulling crimp. Big first move to bomber right hand then, surprisingly hard sequence moving left. Bottom rock quality is great, but once you get through the crux it gets a bit hollow. Its located on the big rock on the north side of the waterfall. Same rock as Mr. Longarm just opposite side.

ascents.comment:
When you don't climb V12 this is the only way to enjoy this glorious boulder!!! So awesome!!

Immediate exposure with quality rock and climbing all the way. I just wish I would have remembered to climb with a beer so I could have stopped part way to take a sap. Only 4 beers short boys.

I actually do not know if I should consider this a flash... The book says climb for a while then rock over wherever.. which i did... but it is like way more aesthetic and fulfilling to go all the way to the tip. And even if I did rock over too early I reversed back into the climb... so I never came off. Ill take the flash.

ascents.comment:
I don't think more fun was ever had at this boulder, nor do I think there ever will be. We had an A+ cast of Drew, Kody, me, AK, and Chase and that turned out to be a recipe for greatness. 

Upgrading to Blue. Not Blue Tag mid you. Just Blue. Movement was actually the most redeeming quality. Watch you elbow!! Those 1-mph collisions can cause serious trauma!

I think another 100 laps and this may clean up enough to be nice.

ascents.comment:
Just west of Kody's cool ultra secret project that no one knows about lives this beauty. Its not very tall, there is a lot of choss, the middle scoop was dripping wet + full of green moss, but it is beautiful nonetheless. 

Start on the low right scoop and move left into the main set of scoops. Much harder than i expected but maybe when the center trench dries and is clean there will be some nice new holds.

ascents.comment:
This boulder is ginormous, like really-really well endowed. Very big pin-pin, if you will. This boulder is just uphill from the super mysterious "Land Survey Monument - Please do not disturb" sign seemingly in no mans land. Maybe I am a recommend slut... but this climb is too good to abstain.  

"Pont du Gard" is on the uphill side and starts on the most obvious feature ever. Amazing ascending jug crack/trough that trends up and right. So many jugs, and just good climbing overall. This is also the down climb since every other part of the boulder is like 25+ feet. 

I would honestly be pretty surprised if this is real FA, the climb just sings so I'm sure someone else heard it before me.

ascents.comment:
I am a firm believer in always having fun when climbing. No matter how shitty the movement, how chossy or how contrived, all climbing should be fun. This climb made me doubt my mantra. 

Just kidding. I had fun. I always do. But damn i may have ruined the rest of my day with the heinous pump. M-soft-first go, and topepd out at the pipe for full value. Unless the pipe is not the accepted finish... in that case i didnt even do the climb.

ascents.comment:
This climb really is fantastic. I think it took 4 sessions so pretty close to redlining. And it only took me 23 tries today; I know the exact number since I have footage. Piece of cake!

Also WTF this climb is so hard, i dont understand. My fat sausages are oozing more than ever before so i just kept rocketing out of that dirty sloot. Was trying to do that steezy had foot match lock off for the first 15 goes but i just got too tired and the hold got too greasy. So i had to settle for pogo. Still cool, but def not steezy!

Also, of everything i touched today the easiest climb was "Street Car Named Desire", i repeated it cause i was in the area. Although now that i think of it my palms dont sweat... only my tips. Bummer. Who do i complain to to fix that genetic defect?

ascents.comment:
Beautiful pinch!! Did I mention I forgot to bring water to Joshua Tree? Like just completely forgot. It wasn't a problem though i never even got thirsty once!! Well i did have a can of coffee and a fresh bell pepper so I'm sure that that was plenty. 

I actually saw a Nature Trail Sign at Cap Rock that said "Plants and Animals in the desert have adaptations to survive in this low water environment. Could you survive? What are your adaptations?".... I think i might behave found my family.

ascents.comment:
This sit was way more inspiring than the stand in my opinion. It just felt like this is what the setter wanted. I know this to be true because I talked to the rock and he said: "I am a sit not a stand, what don't you people get about that!? Where is my good buddy Yabo, I haven't seen that boy in years."

He warmed up to be after a while and thought my beta was quite nice. I used a super strong left toe to pull into a left hand gaston and cross it up. Pretty dope. Barely held the V1 stand move on the send go. Nothing like desperate V1 to sweeten your coffee in the morning.

Last climbing trip before fun-employment ends. Sad in many regards and happy in others. Having money will be nice. 

Should have m-flashed. Ran a warm up burn, to well, warm up and it felt like piss. Missed the jug on that jump because i didn't remember it being so soft. Then my fingers remembered they like to ooze and it got exponentially harder. Still sent, but I was genuinely afraid. 

Good to see my boy Nate. He been done living the live lately.

ascents.comment:
I hate that I am a recommend whore, but when you find a cute climb gruesomely curb stomped and left in the gutter, what would any kind soul do? That's right, you help her out.

This climb, while potentially chossy at the top (no big deal since its only class 3 climbing), it has an awesome gaston lock off (at least the way I did it). Since ive been to bishop tons of time and have never heard of this climb, i feel like the world (well at least my watchers) should at least hear of it. 

There are certainty better sixes but it deserves a look at least and maybe a fondle. Its just to the left of Morning Dove so its not far!

ascents.comment:
Ignacio Sandoval Burn you sweet sweet boy. I am glad you did not die on your endeavor. I am also glad I did not die, on my endeavor. Although at no point did i ever fear for my life and for that I am sorry.  

Truth be told this climb probably took me 20-30 burns over 3 sessions. How is that possible? on a climb with a possible quadriplegic or death fall? Well, I knew this thing was choss at the top, you don't kill people you dont know, thats a rule. Another rule is you scope the top out of dangerous high balls. 

Anyway, I did this climb incrementally one move at a time down climbing between every forward progression. I only pulled on the choicest choss to avoid increased odds of death.

It actually felt like V1 today and the only possibly sketchy hold is the one 25 feet up. No big deal. As long as you pull out not down you good. 

I think this was my first triple fluttering heart! I may repeat this.

ascents.comment:
It was okay. And with that I will use this extra space to talk about everything else from the trip not already in a comment.
  • Great to see Nate out here! Since I start work next week I was just gonna go solo but very nice to share sends and beers with a good friend!
  • I forgot to mention that everything in bishop is easier than everything in JTree. I tried so so hard in Jtree and only managed V5, then come here and with thin oozing skin do V > 5
  • I also did not bring any water to bishop. Unfortunately too because I am losing fitness not carrying around a never drank gas station gallon
  • While I did not have water this weekend, I did have expired Premier Protein shakes, vanilla flavor! While I am sure chemicals in a tetra pack don't ever actually expire, and the taste was still on par, it was like drinking cottage cheese. I could imagine some lesser stomachs gagging and the chunky grimy texture but I think I might be learning to like it.

ascents.comment:
I enjoyed this WAY more than I expected. A V3* traverse, into a no hands rest, into a V5* crux sequence? The numbers certainty don't add up, but we knew it was soft anyway.

I was quite tired from the week so did not think i had any juice left (unless by juice you mean finger tip ooze, in which case i still had plenty) so I was just working the beta so I could m-Flash it next time. But then I found the super plush and very comfortable no hands rest, which was both wildly enjoyable and dramatically increased the softness.

I had never properly read the name of this climb before: "Pappa" "Chubby", basically Fat Daddy. Pretty funny name. 

*grades are a construct

ascents.comment:
I am always surprised when I go to an area I have been to a million times and there are still obscure lines I haven't done! This thing was surprisingly good movement wise, but I guess its made up of mostly choss. 

Carlos and Nate watched from below apparently with a fair amount of terror as I proceed to climb this thing and shower the pads with choss. Id really didn't feel that bad to me. I mean feet felt chossy but all the hands felt solid. Anyway, for those of you who love to obscure chase after me, this is the line to the right of Standing Kill Order! You reach up from the ramp rock to a square blocky hold and climb up!

Very cool seeing Carlos again. Still an incredible human. I just purchased his book on Amazon and it should arrive tomorrow. "The Void Within" by Carlos Tkacz.

ascents.comment: To my glee, I accidentally did this when chalking up and checking durability of the holds for 'Push It'. Free ascents baby!

ascents.comment: One of those climbs that you only do because the rock kinda loos pretty. It really is quite a pretty looking feature I swear! The rock goes from a chossy reddish at the top to a bullet smooth greenish at the bottom. The bottom also has a lot of water sculpted features including one of those big pit like holes that you start in. Starting this is funny because the ground is part of the same rock so kinda impossible not to flash.

ascents.comment: Toward the western edge of lower falls area there is a jumble of rocks that has some really cool features. This is probably the least cool of those features but it is in the recess created by the three or so enclosing boulders. Start below the angle change of the obvious crack in the water sculpted bucket thing. Do easier moves than you though possible and then do the easiest mantle you have imagined... then reverse it to do it again in an even easier way if thats possible.

ascents.comment:
Quick date hike out here with the bae <3. Amazingly, a buffet was just sitting here!! Nice-su!

Anyway this has probably been done but start low on the prominent shelf and go straight up through the second shelf. Ill hopefully get inspired to add it all to MP later so stay tuned.

This whole "Lower Falls" area, as Im calling it, is simply the grouping of boulders lower than the main falls. Its actually just west of the steepest part of the south cliffs and starts where there is a 'beach' like area and continues till a more or less pond looking place starts.

ascents.comment:
Did the direct version to get a bit more climbing in before calling it a day. And what a day it was!! Oh no, not for climbing, I did terrible at that, but today was Chelsea's first day at Joshua Tree!! 

I think it is pretty surprising to see JTree for the first time. It is always magnificent to see the fields of Joshua Trees and endless piles of granite. Even if I know its really just piles of choss, they are still beautiful. 

Stars are always good too. Oh and sunset. Yes. What a day it was!

ascents.comment: Chaseypoo snagged this FA, but I will get Estate Tax so woot woot for me. A great warm up boulder overall, and we found a very contrived line that is going to be virtually impossible to describe. Start to the right of Face Climb, and to the left of Face Climb Center and basically skip all the good holds. Good feet from a right hand gaston gets you to the "plate". Chase got the FA so he can name it and grade it if he wants.

ascents.comment:
Based on true events:
After their fight at the Bridge of Khazad-dm, Gandalf and the Balrog both fell into the deep chasm. Gandalf was burned by the Balrog's fire on the way down, then almost froze in the water at the bottom. He pursued his foe for days through dark tunnels, and then all the way up the Endless Stair to the top of Durin's Tower in the living rock of Zirakzigil, where the two engaged in a two-day long battle at the pinnacle of the Silvertine above the clouds. They fought in a narrow space upon Celebdil, above the mists of the world
-The Lord of the Rings
Area epic my dudes! This is real climbing. Even though I'm pretty sure most falls would hit the landing, and most of those would not tumble past that, there is a very real non-zero chance that you fall a good 50 feet off the canyon wall and die. Located on the west corner of the "Where Eagles Dare Boulder" start standing on opposing jugs and work your way right through the overhang/arete feature.

Start on the on a left-ish facing blocky hold and just move left out of the cave to the good shelf and top out. Draggy but it isn't the worst climb I've ever done.

The time is 4-5 day beers, as Scott and I discuss working, pursuing your passion, the end of the NFL and the baser instincts of human beans.

Because of the time my foot kept picking on the start, but as soon as I stuck the move out right off the greasy grimy chossy Toxic Avenger hold, it was smooth sailing.

ascents.comment:
A line that never should have existed. There just isn't any space between Rave and Last Dance! That being said I am all about contrivance as a means to stave off boredom or create new era movement. 

I think I did this in a new way which is kinda cool. Started as for Rave, then went right hand to the classic broken crimp with my right hand as a gaston. Threw a high left heel and locked that baby down. Crossed left hand up to a small previously un-chalked pocked crimp thing then jumped right to the last dance jugs. Felt harder than "Last Dance" and was pretty cool!

ascents.comment:
The time is definitely 5 day beers now. I see a bunch of people calling this V6. I don't like to be called not Marcellus Wallus, but damn this did not feel like what Chubbs said to do when putting in Happy Gilmore. Rather, I felt like Happy when that gory damn clown wont let my ball through. That being said once I switched to a hockey stick I could put like a pro. 

The holds on the lip as you make the hard moves left felt real bad. Quite fun tho.

ascents.comment:
A frosty little day beer to start your day!! MmmMMmM!!

Three cheers for my boys Scott and Nathaniel! A great weekend filled with day beers, night beers with a small spattering of climbing. Nate's Psyche Tank is pretty low at the moment (you better refill soon my dude) but Scott is still a certifiably crazy insane mofo.

Drove out the the Milks excited to try Soul Slinger but 6 inches of fresh pow pow stopped that quest in its tracks. Luckily I bought and brought chains. My sweet little Hocus Focus proved challenging to install the chains on and drew blood on both Scott and my forearms. The milks are just gorgeous blanked in fresh pow, and a slick icy road proves fantastic for crash pad sketching.  

Anyway, eventually got to the Happys and eventually got to this boulder. Time is irrelevant but it was about 3 or 4 day beers in. Drew and Kody always told me how bad this climb was but I rather enjoyed it. I had dope beta and the victory top out is quite nice.

ascents.comment:
"iWatch Boys!". A more inspiring sentence has never been said when sending this rig. 

News flash Scott hates the word "rig". No idea why. Maybe it makes him thing of those big oil rigs and pollution? Maybe he is afraid of semi-trucks. Who knows. What I do know is that this climb is legitness. Lets do Scotts new proposed star metric for climbs

[*] - Is the climb between 7 and 15 feet tall, with a good landing?
[*] - Are the holds solid?
[*] - Is the line pure?
[*] - Is the movement good?
[*] - Is it aesthetic?

The order of stars are important, don't forget that. Needless to say this is a good ass line. Thank you Scott for those metric. 

Also, soft. I could have sworn I remembered seeing this being V8 which shows that memory is always perfect. I used the sweet extend-O right heel hook, Scott did a sick knee bar. First climb I have done where i pinched a nerve or cut off blood flow or something because my ring finger was completely numb at the top.

ascents.comment:
Guys! Guys!! I did a thing! I used my body and got on top of a thing!! Hooray!

I cant believe this doesn't get even a single little blip of a fluttering heart in the book. Like I could see people getting severely hurt just climbing to the base of the climb itself! 

I think technically most falls would hit the landing, but with a landing significantly  smaller than those little yellow helicopter pads on the tramway towers, landing is not whats worrisome; its bouncing. Bouncing like a bumble all the way down the canyon; possible making the quickest descent to the parking lot possible. At least there is an upside.

Anyway, surprisingly this was my third session over 10 years on this RIG. It came down to one mega trust of a right hand jam to get my left foot up, otherwise it was cake. I will go back with my boy big Scott one of these days because he can and should do it. 

The fact that you can see this line from the parking lot and its inspiring as hell, I am willing to continue my recommend whoring.

ascents.comment: Another area test piece. RPC is shaping up to be quite a nice little San Diego gem of an area. I mean the Whole "PoGo" boulder is gonna blow up with variations I just know it. I can see at least two back side jonses and thats before 5 o clock on a Saturday! Start standing with right hand on the obvious jug and chose your grip, standard, western, or spock. I chose spock which was a little weird at first but then suddenly it just felt right. Left hand on an opposing jug. Work up straight through the sloper depressing using subtle combustion. Very inspiring line.

ascents.comment:
After getting the biggest split of my life attempting Estate Tax, I thought my day was for naught. But I saddled my metaphorical horse one more time and figured I'd try some of the other stuff I had scoped. Boy I was pleasantly surprised. Everything I got on today was super fun with enjoyable movement! Even this dumpity dump dump got my psyched! 

I did the obvious one move stand start a few weeks back and figured I'd look for a lower start. I found one! That one broke, burned down and then sank into the swamp. Just kidding! it just was transmorglified and then shattered into a million pieces. Just kidding again. But seriously the first set of holds I tried to start from shattered. But it meant I had to start slightly lower on slighly stronger holds and those stayed up. Started with double heel toe cams in on the pretty steep (albiet tiny) roof. Make a hard move to the obvious block start of "Garbage Compactor" stand.
ascents.notes:
After getting the biggest split of my life attempting Estate Tax, I thought my day was for naught. But I saddled my metaphorical horse one more time and figured I'd try some of the other stuff I had scoped. Boy I was pleasantly surprised. Everything I got on today was super fun with enjoyable movement! Even this dumpity dump dump got my psyched! 

I did the obvious one move stand start a few weeks back and figured I'd look for a lower start. I found one! That one broke, burned down and then sank into the swamp. Just kidding! it just was transmorglified and then shattered into a million pieces. Just kidding again. But seriously the first set of holds I tried to start from shattered. But it meant I had to start slightly lower on slighly stronger holds and those stayed up. Started with double heel toe cams in on the pretty steep (albiet tiny) roof. Make a hard move to the obvious block start of "Garbage Compactor" stand.

ascents.comment: Sometimes you find amazing things: this is a beautiful bullet rock with crazy patterns. Kind of a shame the roof doesnt have any holds but that sets up a nice desperate throw from river polished slopers on the lip to the top. Starts on a detached part of the boulder and after sticking in a totally mandatory but not needed knee bar, set up on the best part of the slick lip and jump up and left to the good juggy arete. A little harder since the landing really isnt that good, but its not very high so I think youll pull through. I bet the straight campus from the slopers goes, but it might be V9 alone.

ascents.comment:
From my driveway to the boulders was 25 minutes. A 14 minute drive and 11 minute jog (with a soft J). I've been making goose egg trips out to RPC, desperately trying to finish up "Estate Tax" before it gets swooped by another strong-strong boi. 

I actually came out on Friday as well (one aforementioned of those goose egg performances) and broke my favorite hold off of "Estate Tax"! I was a sad-sad boi that day. I was so sure it would go down... and i guess it did, but not in the way I wanted. Anyway, don't worry my dear-dear bois, the project still goes but now slightly more contrived and slightly harder. Probably solid V9 now. 

That all being said its Poison Oak season everyone! Be careful! I trimmed a bunch on Friday (and my poor sister Eileen somehow got the devils itch on her forearm). I also moved a bunch or rocks from the landing to cover up a lot of that poison oak and after lowering the landing by maybe 6 inches a lower start to "The Penthouse" felt quite natural. 

So to prevent another my poor body from having to lay another goose egg I sent this one move extension of "The Penthouse". It was a very soft V7 before so maybe now its solid for the grade? Start with the cool right hand pinch thing and any lower left hand.

ascents.comment:
PN (Proposed Name): This is usually just referred to as "The right arete of Italian arrogance". Sit start with left hand on the low under cling and right hand up pinching the arete. Some slaps and tension lead to better holds (the ones you start "American Ignorance" on), from which you can pull directly up using a black xeno. Glad to find beta that was not Drews original beta. 

Shoutout Drew for beeing a baller (apparently he is scared of bees now). After climbing a full day at Woodson, when all the weenies bailed, drew ran out with me to RPC to slay some area classics and take down the "Tax Evasion" project. I wonder what clever terrible name he is cooking up. Thank you for intentionally not sending the "Estate Tax", I am pretty sure you could have finished it and for that you have my thanks.

ascents.comment:
PRNF: This is in all likelihood not an FA but if no one corrects me ill take it. 

I wanna shout out my Valley Bois: Chase and Kody. I don't mean 'Valley' as in they enjoy Yosemite (or Mineral King, which they do). I mean it as in if you were to plot their psyche and climbing ability as a time series they would be in a serious dip. 

Kody I was very happy to climb with you at Woodson. I really hope you come back and share some more beers with me. I also really hope when that time comes you will slap up that rightward sloping chodler with me. I know you will have a good time. Also RPC is just waiting for you... as am I. 

Back to the climb: This thing stand starts on the juggiest part of the right arete of the Italian arrogance boulder. Traverse left through the slight shelf and join the top of the standard Italian Arrogance. Pretty cool movement actually. Cant wait to do the sit of "America" into this which drew said he will name "America F*** Yeah" which I really hope he does, because its an awesome name.

ascents.comment: So should have flashed, but used wrong foot at crux. Cant really decide if I like this problem overall or not but i loved one move. After exiting the roof I end up with left hand on a shitty minipinch and a good left foot and needing to bump the right hand. What makes this great is the hold I bump to is about an inch away from my face. Pretty funny to seem so close but still be far! If only I had fingers on my face (as long as they were washed)

ascents.comment:
Every time I told someone I had not done this they responded with 'Wow! I cant believe YOU haven't done that soft piece' (shoutout Jenny, Scott, et al.). They were all absolutely right, but this was a serious epic for me! Too much delicateness and balance for this brute. Soul Slinger has been on my mind even since Chase popped his V9 cherry on it (or maybe ever since Key-Lime started projecting it), but I failed session after session. My last 3 times to bishop, the Milks were snowed out, so I was relieved to finally get a rare opportunity Morty. High wind was pretty optimal for maximizing friction with hands as wet as mine. Great to knock you nemisis out early in the trip that way you can start drinking beer earlier... although pretty sure I was already a beer or two deep at this point. Nice work Erik on the quick send yourself! 
	
Really amazing how impossible this thing originally felt and how easy it feels when dialed. Truly an great rock climb!

ascents.comment:
Sandbox took this beauty out for the best date of her life. Started with a casual walk on the beach, a homecooked meal at sunset and a shared bottle of Pinot Noir snuggled near the fire with the soothing pitter patter of rain outside. Translation: we gangbanged this rig. 
	
	I had never seen anyone working this but its gets 2 stars in the book so figured I'd try. Shortly after we had almost 10 Sand men + women at the top. Fun sequences with intersting holds and movement. Awesome to see the beta change over burns and hone in on the 'softest' optimal sequence. 
	
	Always a pleasure to be objectified and used for your body.

ascents.comment:
Now is the time for David Vasko's long diary entry:
	
	This trip was the reunion of 13 longtime UCLA friends spanning the Sandbox and outlying areas: Pictured from left to right in the only group picture taken: Erik, Ari, Jacquie, Kelsey, Drew, Chase, Micro, Jenny, Gregor, Nate, Akhil, Jessa and Tomasso. It was the worst of times, it was also the best of times. Amazing to see everyone but I wish it wasn't under the doom and gloom that is Corona. Many of these friends I have not seen in years and despite all that time and distance our reunion was timeless. Literally felt like we had all just walked out of 529 1/2 on our way to pizza after a session of climbing in John Wooden. Unreal. Everyone looks exactly the same, I wonder who will get fat first. 
	
	Classic warm up on sunshine boulder with no pads, classic day beers 'mmMmMM!', classic butt touching (sPOTDing), classic bleeding fingers, classic crash pad island, not so classic house to crash in, neo-classic dinner at the Rambler, not at all classic at all lack of hackey sack, classic douchbaggery from the sandboxes biggest douchbags, classic asshole-ery from your biggest assholes, classic Erik still being a strong-strong boi, classic sandbox tanks, and more classic and non-classic items. 
	
	On my way to Bishop from San Diego I stopped in Upland to drop off my girlfriend. As I get out of my car there is an audible hissing noise which was soon determined to be my front left tire loosing air at an alarming rate. So I take it into the shop and they tell me its a miracle none of my other tires had popped. I proceeded to replace all 4, which was perfectly timed to pick up chase at 5pm. I wonder if I shoudl still be amazed that my life works out so well. If it hadn't started hissing then i bet it would have popped way out in the table lands.
	
	I was also riddled with poison oak which was not so sick. Glad the asshole fears turned out to be just fears... itchy fears... 
	
	Now place your bets in this Corona Pool! Winner take all!

ascents.comment:
Second Ascent. Surprise send this one. Was literally warming up on the moves while I waited for non-existent clouds to give me better temps on "Estate Tax". No expectation of sending at all. I thought this was harder than "Estate Tax" but that obviously wasn't true. I also thoughr this was probably V10 but that also obviously wasn't true. Start move felt okay so I gave it a ground go and held on. I think perfect heel hook and toe hook beta makes cruxes easier. 

Came out to RPC today despite my better judgement, regarding the pandemic. Had not left my house since last Sunday night, and almost didn't go today but I was afraid Drew would cruise "Estate Tax" and I want the V10FA points, I really do Brian. I was honestly afraid someone would chastise me for breaking Corona Isolation at RPC but instead I saw swarms of people (and a rattlesnake). Like seriously there were more people than a normal Saturday. I even saw an extremely nice ranger (or wild life volunteer) and instead of warning me about Corona they warned me to be gentle to the wildlife. Oh that and watch out for poison oak, at which I showed them my ravaged arms which are riddled with it. No one was 6 feet apart. It's like no one is worried. Sigh. I hope this pandemic doesn't get too bad here in Cali. Wash you hands and don't touch your face.

ascents.zlaggableName: Well, it's not a pry bar
ascents.comment:
Wanted to see how hard breaking "Estate Tax" would be by going from the "Penthouse" jug right into "Estate Tax". Started left hand in the good right facing jug you cross to on "The Penthouse" and right hand in a slightly smaller right facing jug just below. Pull yourself on and make a few slightly extended gaston moves to get into the top out of "Estate Tax Project". 

Kinda fun but this climb will most certainly and seriously decrease the life span of that already hollow jug flake. Might make a cool Extension to "The Penthouse" or "Tax Evasion".

Harder than I expected without using the better more friable jugs. And way more hard coming into this from "The Penthouse": when you come in from "The Penthouse" your right hand is in the better part and matching is real tough and gross. Making "The Penthouse" cross into the worse part of the jug would be real difficulty... may have to think on this extension.

ascents.comment:
I've been making weekly trips out to RPC trying to send "Estate Tax", but the project is still open. Next week for sure!

I have been loving biking to the boulder from my house which takes about 30 minutes to get to the boulder (5.5 miles), and about 35 minutes home. I bike with my big organic pad so I'm sure I look pretty rad! 

This climb is in the narrow corridor between Mr. Longarm and The Penthouse. Insanely difficult to not dab, and feet are pretty poopy.  Might be soft, I felt terrible.

Start on the right side of the boulder on a ledge and move left through some big features. Butterflies like the water section. Chelsea likes butterflies. A kaleidoscope is a group of butterflies.

ascents.comment: First FA for bounders 6! Likely not an actually FA but i will be the first to log it on 8a. On the Timber gap trail, when you hit the flat open meadow-ish section before you hit the wooded part of the gap, the hills just sing. You will know you are there because of the singing. My father calls this section of the trail "The Sound of Music" and this FA is an ode to that. Start on the West side of the boulder with both hands on a large ledge. Mantle up onto the ledge the finish up.

ascents.comment: Actually looked at this years ago with Chase, Drew and Nathaniel but tired eyes and dry psyche blurred our "line" vision. Immaculate rock quality, with good body tension and an irresistable back flag make this climb quite good. After sending this I had enough psyche to propel me up FLorence peak (20.5 total miles)! I gained enough ground on the final switchbacks to the pass, that I figured I had time to test the scramble. Quite fun, and another peak in the valley checked!

ascents.comment: A surprisingly fun line on this crumble pile of a boulder. Start in the center-right of the crumbling feature and move right from the crumbling feet to cool crimps and ultimately a tough rock over to better top out. Trying to blitzkrieg some climbs while we wait for our hiker gang to re-group!

ascents.comment: I actually did this one almost a decade ago but never filmed it so it never happened. This one starts on the south end of the boulder that the Alpine Chalet (now called Paradise Ridge) sits. Start both hands on the obvious ledge and find a way to mantle up

ascents.comment: Same start but eliminate all holds to left and do a big thrutch right to the slopers on the overhanging lip. Match up and mantle up moving right to make mantle easier. You have now discovered secert passage to the Alpine (now Paradise Ridge) Chalet! Way to go!

ascents.comment: On the creek side of the Alpine Chalet, there is a cool rock with a small overhanging lip. Literally 20ft to the left when looking at the firepit. Start on the obvious pinch edge  directly below the overhang and move left ultimately to grab a jug sidepull. As a bounus grab some of the discarded half burnt logs to help your fire!

ascents.comment: I would say 4 pads is the bare minimum. I scrambled up the talus field with 4 Pads (3 big and a metolius), and it was rather tiring. This feels surprisingly exposed as soon as you pull on, and a few slaps certainty get the heart rate going. Probably closer to V5 but that gets the scare and pad carrying grade. Squeezing in some early morning climbing to make the most of my last day in paradise!

ascents.comment: A link up of "The Penthouse Low" into "Well, its not a pry bar". Is probably V8, but it took me a surprising amount of sessions. I think an easier sequence could lock it in at V8, so i reserve the right to downgrade when it sees some action. Its contrived as hell, all good holds past "the penthouse" jug are off, which forces a hard match to start "Well its not a pry bar". Estate Tax next trip i swear!

ascents.comment: Interesting. Cool start hold and really cool mantle shelf at the end (about 15 feet up!). For the crux move I had to do some weird pointer middle finger psuedo-pocket in the crack and rock over a heel using that. I'm sure there is an easier way but damn that crack bites!

ascents.comment:
This thing has some inspiring holds. So many beautiful flat ledges that I just had to touch. It is a traverse so, i'm afraid it may have a tough life. Poor climb, be nice if you can. 

We also ended up making today's adventure even more fun by scoping "Natalie". Steep hikes, skipping rocks and marsh crossing were some of the highlights here. We had an almost 12 hour day out at way! So much adventuring!

ascents.comment: What an adventure!! Not the climb (that, while cool was rather simple) The adventure I am talking about is the scamper Kody, Chase and I did all about the Talus! We were looking for Avada Kadavera so we proceed to spend at least 1.5 hours going all the way up through upper talus, back down, back up, around and through, all the way to grandmothers house. When we were about to give up we dropped all our pads and fanned out. After about 30 minutes we realized we were 5 feet away it looked dumb.

ascents.comment:
Wish you all could have been there to watch the Fantastic Shirley Show. The amount of times that man threw himself at Meadow Roof was simple INSPIRING! Wow! Emmy deserving 

Was pretty destroyed but figured id flail on Crimp Ladder one last time in case the unthinkable and I sent. I didn't, but i did increase days climbed metric. 

Hiking all around with my double Big Organic and sufficient beer certainty tired me this weekend. Fitness baby! Now to fit some double nut browns into my mouth hole!

ascents.comment:
This thing is nuttier than pecan pie. Aesthetics are busting out the hull, movement is prettier than a mermaid figure head, and scare factor is "You best start believing in ghost stories miss Turner, yer in one!"

Tried this one 50-100 times over several years. Looks scary, but that last move is impossible to prepare for. Even with 8 large organics... still made 3 sad boys and 2 non-sad boys quiver in their boots. 

Thanks Kody for the "I think I had him" spot. Don't perish into the locker!

I've been to scared... and now that I'm a sad boy I don't know if i could handle it. But if you fell... well maybe you might want to have brought the headstone. I hope no one dies in Grave of the Fireflies... or on it now.

ascents.comment:
I told the boys this was V1 but after realizing it took me 4 tries, albiet without chalk and only cruizers... I decided they were right and gave it V2. Much more better.

This rock is few minutes after the Eagle-Mosquito split on the down hill side of a glorious look out rock. Surprisingly there is a small overhang with a huge fin that leads to an enjoyable dead point. 

Despite the moderately smoky conditions.. enjoy that Puff.. puff Panorama Boys!

Also this thing is too hard for Kody

ascents.comment:
What a beautiful block! movement is good too! Someone strong should try the V15 to the right.

A few things I cant believe. (1) Scott thought this was more natural to start one move in. Seriously!? God gives you a glorious pinch and you start one move in! As drew said "Yeah that definitely starts matched on the pinch". (2) Scott thought this was V8! Bah. He couldn't even do Ranger Cave! rofl. (3) How amazing this block is. It even has an incredible chilling cave.

ascents.comment: Looks like its going to be trivially easy, but then it packs a punch. The starting angle is kinda tricky then the top is way more airy then you want after a 4 mile approach. Very aesthetic chunk of rock which just sings like a beautiful piano melody by Joe Hisashi.

ascents.comment:
The Igor Wall is incredible. Quality, Quantity and Proximity. Only negative is the top outs, but maybe when we rope it up we will find a more enjoyable top. This line doesn't care about that tho, since is Pure, like the Project. Rather frustrating! The final move is huge like her tracks of land.

Shout out Drew Chase Kody Scott and Eileen for joining me on another unforgettable trip to MK.  Thank you from the bottom of my heart, I hope you enjoyed it as much as i did. See yalls here next time!

ascents.comment: I did this thing on my first day rope climbing outside over 10 years ago. Back then it was hard and I had to try and crimp feet. Today I m-flashed and actually crack climbed! Started the train with yer boy Zev. I guess I can confidently say I am slightly better. Incredible crack, that's all there is to say! Oh the downclimb is the crux for us boulderers.. reversing a crack is wack. First time for everything.

ascents.comment:
Left entrance. I know grades are hard to translate sometimes from Rope to Boulder... but this thing could and probably should be V7. We did it ground up and while I'm sure it would have felt a little easier with temps, this has a mono lock off and a dead point like to the lip like 20 feet high.

Regardless, simply incredible. Aesthetic, with great moves and even the mono is satisfying! Awesome weekend with my boy Zev! Sad MK fell through but it turned out pretty dope.

ascents.comment:
Scott asked me to reschedule our date to Wednesday that way he could that way he could save himself during our date and work out the following day at full strength in the gym. What a crazy man. Some people may have been offended, but Scott and I know each others bodies. He literally drove out to Mickeys just for some brief camaraderie, ambiance and stories of love. 

He also said "Im getting an appreciation for the coast. I don't like the beach or the ocean but its a great background". Legend.

Her feet may be 5 sizes smaller than mine, but my climbing shoes worked just fine. No send for her, but shes hooked! Big Shout out to Kristie for letting me WFH at her house, and share an amazing week with more than copious amounts of wine! Handstands, coffee, Hamilton, smoothies, lost wallets, forgotten power cords. Amazing week!

Thank you Scott and Drew for bringing me out.

ascents.comment: My JAM! A little bit of squeezing followed by a very unique mantle!! Squeezing part is probably about V6, and the mantle alone is probably V7... but I am a Mantle Wizard so kind of hard to tell. Dialed the mantle in isolation after a few goes, then it took about 6 tries or so from the ground! Very stoked on this one especially because I didn't know it was a project at the time. Monkey saw a mantle, monkey had to do the mantle!

ascents.comment: Surprised myself with this one! I didn't expect to be able to stick the first move so I played on the dyno once before trying from the ground. Kristie winning the doggie bjorn lottery getting to carry that pup!

ascents.comment: This is on your way to "Ashley to Classy" ( I now know its actually "Ashy to Classy" but my ear holes dont werk sometimes okay).  Its the boulder in the channel right before Ashy to Classy, big move from a large hollow-ish clake to a nice mantle lip encounter. Scott and I had a nice moment enjoying the top out together, sharing a laugh, and just absorbing each others company. ALSO drews new goggles wrecked his depth perception. Tall man hit ground harder than expected

ascents.comment: North face of the "data and picard" boulder. Start right hand on an underclinggy pocket feature and left hand on an incut smallish crimp thing. One hard right hand slap leads to easy but slightly airy climbing to join Data and Picard. Kinda sad since there are a ton of cool pockety features but almost none of them are fully utalized.

ascents.comment: I amaze myself by somehow finding even more contrived and or smaller,  and or dumber lines every time. So if you are looking at "Data and Picard" look left. Hop over the small channel and this boulder is directly in front of you. Yes its small, I'm AWARE. navigate around the left side which is in the creek. There is a series of left facing holds over the creek and just enough cheat stones to establish.  Pull a slightly scary "I don't want to get wet" move up and left to a good hold and top out.

ascents.comment:
Quite contrived, but good movement.  Start as for "Leisure Lagoon" but make a big move up and right to the obvious sloper. No, No, 
 no topping out yet, you must traverse right all way around the corner. Match up that sloper the use some great jugs on the corner to work around it and then top out on the side that faces due west.

ascents.comment: On the boudler on the north side of data and picard, tha tone basically touching it but not, yeah its really little. Start on the right side and climb leftward using the arete. Eileen getting pumped on this rig! lol.

ascents.comment: Surprisingly enjoyable. This boulder is on the north side of the Data and Picard boulder, almost touching it but not quite. Start on the left side of this boulder on two pretty good holds, and use the namesake out right to start.

ascents.comment: Start "Tea, Earl Grey, Hot" but one move lower... thats why its HOTTTER. Just wait there is definitely going to be a HOTTEST. Left hand Gaston-ing the big spock side pull and right hand out right on the crimp on the face (the left hand for 'When I plucked the rose'.

ascents.comment: When crossing the river to Data  and Picard, if you look to your left you might see this shit pile. No not because its bad (its not great), but because there was bird poop all over the start hold (not start hold). If you started there it would probably only be V1, but the climb is over water so to get to the start hold you have to downward traverse in from the left. Surprisingly the most interesting moves are the moves to get you to the "starting" blocky hold. Hard not to dab the water!

ascents.comment: Contrivance to the max. Start almost as for "That tree is far away" but intentionally don't use the jug, and also off rout all jugs for the rest of the climb. Not bad movement really but when you gotta start putting tape on an outdoor problem so people can even understand.... its a little much. Oh and i literally got ants in my eyes on this one.

ascents.comment: Shoutout Pichael for saving this GPS coordinate in his phone, 5 years ago and hilariously saving it as "A Nice Boulder". Would not have re found this without his coordinate. Great broken features on a 20+ foot tall boulder. This version juts up an left through the jug seam toward the channel. Its nice because if you climb V0 and get scared here you can bail into the channel, but for full value use the knobs to wrap around slightly and top out all the way!

ascents.comment: A fun little Chimney right as a cluster of boulders starts! Always amazing to see split boulders like this and be able to see exactly how they used to fit together. Eileen tends to get claustrophobic but stepped up for this one! Also for the Diary portion, made Joel try a corner of this boulder that turned out to be free rock and fell spectacularly.

ascents.comment: Awesome features: heucos in granite, and the pinch is to die for! Was not able to start matched on the under cling as I originally wanted, so had to start left hand already on the pinch. It might go from the low but the feet might be too bad. Its fern time of year so name is apt. Not a very tall boulder but the features make it worth. It all boils down to a pendulum move up and right.  Got dark quick, hanks Joel for bringing our only illumination.

ascents.comment: An obvious "nose" feature behind the "Less is" climbs. A slightly awkward dabber rock to your left leads to a delicate arete/sloper crux to navigate the nose. Pretty sure any climb that looks like these nose features probably always ends up with some sort of nose reference or pun. Amazingly there is another very similar looking nose a few football fields up the ridge that I was not able to try due to time constraints. Kinda cool to have two so close!

ascents.comment: This is a king line. The direct finish on "A Nice Boulder" through the amazing xenos and flakes. 20ish feet of amazeballs. Thank you All Might for your always inspiring presence and phrases.  So amazing to come full circle on this boulder after seeing it ~5 years ago and thinking "Wow that's cool but i will NEVER be back here", turns out I came back! Also good try on picking up that water bottle Eileen!

ascents.comment: Cool features (some are a little too hollow to be great) on a vertical face lead to fun slopey top out. A stones throw from "Silver Lining".

ascents.comment: A very easy crack I did on the more open ridge that Joel and Eileen were exploring. Did a handstand at the top.

ascents.zlaggableName: I get it, I'd just rather go to bed
ascents.comment: Jamie's step father Robert making his presence known with this killer quote. As for the climb, tucked away an a channel between bigger boulders, start beneath and make one hard slap to the redeeming xeno features.
ascents.notes: Jamie's step father Robert making his presence known with this killer quote. As for the climb, tucked away an a channel between bigger boulders, start beneath and make one hard slap to the redeeming xeno features.

ascents.comment: Good Scoping Joel! I would not have even seen this. On the small boulder in front of "A nice boulder" there is a sequence of HUGE scoop jugs that climb naturally up the side.
ascents.notes: Good Scoping Joel! I would not have even seen this. On the small boulder in front of "A nice boulder" there is a sequence of HUGE scoop jugs that climb naturally up the side.

ascents.comment: Second boulder we stopped at on the Silver City Ridge adventure. This area starts a decent cluster of climbable boulders. This particular one is a small boulder that is actually a large flake of the one above it, you get to top out the flake and top out the subsequent boulder too. Eileen FA'ed the natural right exit, this version is explicitly on the flake using the small crimps.

ascents.comment: This is one of those climbs where dyno-ing is actually easier than climbing. Like "Less is Less" start on the seam , only using features on the flake, but instead of crimping like Floop is mad, do a huge DP to the lip. Kinda cool! Also anyone know how to log a climb as First Go, but not flash since you did another climb that started in the same place?

ascents.comment: Anyone else feeling rock deprived these days? Makes me feel thankful to still find untouched granite that I can call mine. An ode to all those people who can never get enough rock. This is the first rock we stopped at when heading up the ridge behind silver city, a kind of technical arete into a slopey top crux. Some really cool xenos and crack system on the death fall side, but not worth the risk way out here.

ascents.comment: AMAZING slab crack! Super obvious and super good. Me Eileen and Joel running Train on this piece! My sister is a BADASS, she hasn't climbed in forever and easily sacks up for this kinda tall, slightly scary climb! Joes follows suit already giving this 3 ascents!! Very cool mid mantle into a pod, followed by some good crack feet or technical face smears. Can sit start for slightly more difficulty, but doesn't add any fun.

ascents.comment: Rather good. A offset section of boulder creates a under cling feature all the way up! One "trust" issue move at the top but in general good feet all the way. Might be a dyno variation that would be rad... if i'm ever back here that is lololol.

ascents.comment: On the backside of "The Garden of Elrond", start on an obvious left hand and a smaller crimp out right. Smear feet for a move to the lip then mantle. A ridiculous lie down start may be possible. This area is worth visiting for the beauty alone, climbing is secondary. Must do.

ascents.comment: Careful Mr. Nazgul! If you are not careful you may fall into the torrent that is horses made of living water! A beautiful block that sports a odd hop start and a slightly worrisome mantle ensues. Picturesque!

ascents.comment: The Waterfall is gorgeous. I have never been all the way down and this time of year when the water is low enough to expose the perfect river worn features, and allow closer inspection is fantastic. This obvious line starts ins a body sized river worn hole, next to a much larger feature which has water running year long. Its basically a cylinder hole. The climb is simply to start in that hole and mantle out! Way to go Eileen for doing this!

ascents.comment: Tried desperately to force this line to start one hold lower, because as is its like an easy 1 move campus... this is the only climb done in the very disappointing talus field on the south side of the Kaweah river beneath the waterfall. IF i managed to do the hard start it would have added a wild slap and swing.. but oh well... will never be back here and as that homeless guy in Mr. Deeds says...

ascents.comment: The beauty of this area is overwhelming. Especially now with fall colors add into the mix it humbles the mind. This climb is near the hacking grounds Me Eileen and Joel used. Start on a bad sloper and a tiny crimp rendered usable because of a great heel toe cam,  and either do a cool double gaston sequence, or power your way up to the better sloper. Good find Eileen!

ascents.comment: Amazing boulder quite close to the Resort itself! How awesome. Name is a tribute to the amazing author Brandon Sanderson who continues to mystify my brain and transform my world. Seemingly bare rounded arete has just enough holds to make it amazing. to the left of "Ranger Rock" to the right of the burnt stump.

ascents.comment: The kids call this boulder "Ranger Rock", so who am I to rob that from them? They are kids so they are obviously too weak to send this but I will honor them.  From Silver City head down the road with houses on the opposite side of the resort and take a right at the first fork. This will be on the left as you get to a grass clearing.

ascents.zlaggableName: Follow Every Toast with a Song
ascents.comment: Start as for Data and Picard but make a cool left hand cross all the way to the pocket. From their finish up "Tea, Earl Grey, Hot", but uh oh! your hands are flipped!!! What ever will you do? First V8 at RPC lolol.

ascents.comment: The best part of this boulder is the crazy scoop features that you end up laying in to start it. A little moisture and you have a grade A slide! Physically not possible with a pad since there isn't room. On the west side of "The Cavern" area,there is a flat rail. Start there and go up and left desperately trying not to dab.

ascents.comment: I thought this was going to be easier... i mean the jug is so close! But alas, because the ground is so close its hard to generate left. Had to use some smaller holds to allow a match before popping a back side jones to stick the ka-wham into the jug.

ascents.zlaggableName: When I Plucked the Rose Sit
ascents.comment: Start left hand same spot but start right hand about 2.5 feet lower and half a foot left of your left hand. Yeah its that subtle foot used for some other climbs. Rule #1, DONT use the big feature underneath the starting ledge for feet. I used some downward facing foot on the bottom of the ledge itselt, but the lower feature feels like basically the ground so why not just walk up. Cool shoulddery left lock off!

ascents.comment: Another forced line that almost forces you to get wet. This thing is basically opposite Wet Cheeks, int the bottom pond. A fairly sit start hold exists and at least in summer there is enough dry rock under you to actually sit (just barely). A little awkward since there really isnt much space to move your ass, without getting wet.

ascents.comment: Wow they force you to give # of attempts but the number doesn't go above 100! This was my project a the beginning of COVID and since then I have probably tried it around 200 times. I went about every week since March. Cloud 9 baby! Beer tastes good.  I also wish there was no comment length so I could go on a long Tirade. FAs are soft, everyone knows that. Come do it and downgrade, you wont! Was going to be the best V8 until the fin broke. Homer will tell tales of this. Not Mike, the Grecian one.

ascents.comment: It was wet snow. . . . top holds felt quite oozy. . . so i instead went left hand to a right facing gaston, and then just popped right hand cross from the under cling to the top. Wonder if anyone else ahs done it that way. Chase was not happy because if i fell  during this insane move i would have crushed his son. His son was an immovable pile of gloom at the time.

ascents.comment: Certainty soft but i think we hit a small window of perfect temps when we did the stand because the crux quickly started to feel harder and harder. I choose you, Pickachu Jesus! I mean if i have my choice that is.

ascents.comment: Great rock climb with slightly odd first move. Thank you Chase and Marina for bringing me to Rock Creek for my first time! Wow! Not a huge area but some serious quality! Good temps quickly leading to "too good" of temps as snow flurries start to fall... stay tuned to find out if it was dry snow.... or wet snow! Dun! Dun! Duuuuuuun!

ascents.comment: I started both hands on the face crimps... but even starting with left hand already up felt hard. Still waiting to find out if that was wet or dry snow... we'll tell you after this short message from our sponsor.

ascents.comment: Honestly this looked way cooler that it felt. Don't get me wrong its definitely a great rock climb, but I just expectation bummed myself. This Bishop season teeing up to be quite the plushness. Very glad to be starting a paid subscription to climb V11 this season.

ascents.comment: Post break. Quarantine skin is thin, so wasn't even gonna try but chase made it look soooo easy I just had to. Very nice lock off! Aftermath was only two sliced and bloody tips, but luckily, neither were mine!

ascents.comment: Holy Gronk-amole! Thanks NFL newscaster for that beautiful pun on my STUD. Also this climb is confusing where to start and HARD. I started left hand on  the arete and right hand on an underling, and summoned all the strength inside me to get my ass of the ground, then magically move my right hand fast enough to catch the slopey lip and swing and also try desperately not to dab or fall off.  Had to run it back because of a micro-dab first send.

ascents.comment: The ending of this seems rather arbitrary. I got to the Hamtaro holds so i figure thats good enough. Mortal Combat next time baby!!! Im gonna go all Scorpion and rip the spine out if you know what i mean.

ascents.comment: This V3 is the crux of the V7, in fact its the only "meat" of the climb if you will. Although I don't eat meat so maybe the "nuts" of the climb. That sound nice.

ascents.comment: V7 in the new book and I'm taking it!! Good temps certainly help this, but that V3 top is quite the heart breaker. Glad I brought some nice frosty Double Nut Brown for your troubles!

ascents.comment: Felt utterly impossible. Then i switched shoes, got bit by a radioactive spider, did a pec dance in front of a mirror and voila! I got some technique! I haven't been to the buttermilks in too long. These bullet patina holds are pavlovian.

ascents.comment: With "Working Class" this boulder actually actually offers the bouldering world a decent set of climbs! Plus its close to the Bachar Problems, so its rather surprising these don't see more action. Small and interesting with crux top outs.

ascents.comment: Smith you should be embarrassed having done it. But hey! Days climbed metric baby! Always a silver lining.

ascents.comment: A little boulder walked into a bar and said, "Bartender, give me a cup of your finest Wiskey, on the rocks please!". The bartender  dusted off a fine bottle and asked "will this do?", the boulder said. "yessir". The bartender opened the bottle and poured poured it on the little bouders head and said "I love puns. Dont take life for granite. This ones one me.. well technically its on you ... but its on me"

ascents.comment: May not have gone as far right as I was supposed to now that I am reading the book. I followed the blue line... but the book says rightward AS FAR AS POSSIBLE. hmm. Oh well.

ascents.comment: Finally made it out to Lake Ramona!!! T'was just a quick little exploratory session, but had to at least do something new. Definitely checks the box for low ball classic! Ante Meridian and Ariel Charriot look amazballs.

ascents.comment: msoftflash This has always felt so improbable. It boils down to one slopey crimp that you back flag off with one arm and hope the friction doesnt blow. Today it felt like piss. Was thinking V9 until today, because truth is its just friction dependent. Start as for "Data and Picard" make the cool left cross to the pocket as for "Follow Every Toast with a Song" but instead of going up, continue right across the face w/ a cool backflag match thing. Might be "breakable" for tall bois w/ high gaston

ascents.comment: After climbing at Woodson enough... I have finally realized the boulder grades here are as wacky as Jim Carey on crazy pills. I read a discourse on what this climbs "boulder" grade should be and people argue passionately for as low as V4 and as high as V8! This thing is STOUT and will put most v7/v8 climbers on their asses. Its literally a forearm pump machine with a tricky top. That being said, incredible feature and my personal grade is V6. Can you deal with that!

ascents.comment: What a LOVELY Thanksgiving! My brother wisely cancelled thanksgiving due to several illnesses across the family, so I way the rare opportunity and went climbing. I also did this thing without the Black Xeno by going straight up the prow and it felt like the same grade.

ascents.comment: Sit Start. Start from your ass on a left hand slot crimp thing and right hand sloper. Two tough moves get you into the standard start. Certainly harder than the original but the original was pretty soft so this probably just solidifies the grade rather than bumps it.
ascents.notes: Sit Start. Start from your ass on a left hand slot crimp thing and right hand sloper. Two tough moves get you into the standard start. Certainly harder than the original but the original was pretty soft so this probably just solidifies the grade rather than bumps it.

ascents.comment: The overhanging "nose" up and right from King Nothing. Start right hand on crimp and jump for the side pull meat hook thing for your left. Slap your hands and choss your feet rightward to ultimately get yourself into the jugular tube feature. A direct press may be possible, as well as a left escape.  Most of Woodson's unexplored rock is either completely blank or perfect choss. This climb is more of the latter, but cool feature nonetheless.

I did mantle the big fin to start which was kidna cool but its too easy, too forced and too in an awkward spot so it doesn't really have any redeeming qualities. Plus I had to top out into a bush then immediately downclimb which was.. well.. something.

ascents.comment: From "I for an Eye" head directly west. You will pass a very obvious and very chossy prow. This is just passed the sideways tree on the same boulder as the chossy prow. Sit start low in two jugs and move up through a very cool groove feature with some huge side pulls. Move a little right to help ultimately move upward. How did I forget beer today!!! Bad llama.

ascents.comment: From "I for an Eye" head directly west. This is the very obvious and very chossy prow. Hopefully as you pull on the holds you don't go out like the real Hanging Gardens and erase yourself from the face of the earth. Once nice perk when its this chossy, it kina sounds like rain while your are climbing which is a relaxing sound. Plus unlike real rain it isn't wet.

ascents.comment: The sharp arete feature that comes out of a dang it hole to the right of "The River Tigris". This one fights back! Put me on my ass once and put me shoulder first into the back rock a few times. Very cool arete with a plethora of cool edges to crimp on. Techy feet make this one much more of a puzzle than it looks at first. Landing isn't great but just cover up the hole with a pad and you forget its there.

ascents.comment: Yes!! This is the climb that made me seek Lake Ramona. Beyond fantastic with aesthetics in every category. Amazing rock and equally amazing view. Great movement AND I've unlocked a shorter friendly beta so now no excuses for not coming to LR. I love that the area overview for LR on MP still says: "The boulders on the hilltop west of Lake Ramona are enticing from afar but less appealing when you get closer. Mostly a nice destination for a morning hike." How wrong they were!

ascents.comment: Short and squeezy!! My Jam. Felt like basically one hard slap, but luckily this corridor stays pretty cool and had a breeze so friction was good. It's short and I'm good at squeezing so hard for me to accurately grade. I looked terrible on the top out. I think I did the worm.

ascents.comment: This thing is INCREDIBLE; all variations are fantastic. I wonder how many people you could fit on this boulder at one time? Perfect angle with Pavlovian texture. Like seriously I'm drooling right now. Taller than you expect which just means more surface area to play! Honestly one of the most perfect slabs I have EVER been on. If you could somehow copy this and put it on an angle adjuster, it would be really awesome to see how steep the friction would hold.

ascents.comment: Probably more like V2, but its tall and scary so Ill give you the bonus point. The Fractured Boulder continues to deliver. This climbs the crazy "s" like double angle change arete. One hard move down low gains you the second tier arete, and climbing eases significantly. Despite this entire boulder having incredible rock quality, the very apex of the boulder is shit and aptly also has shit. Bird shit that is. So take care on your journey! Yay me contributing to LR!

ascents.comment: This climb is one of my favorite from the day! Such varied and fun movement on an incredibly gorgeous piece of rock. Only con is that it faces south so it gets hammered by that totally inconsiderate burning ball of gas in the sky. Shade felt cool, but while working this I felt like I was in the devils asshole. Honestly felt more like V6 or V7 to me but that could have just been due to that asshole thing, and the fact the ideal beta took a bit to find.

ascents.comment: Honestly not sure if I started in the correct place, but I climbed something. Not as good as Babyface but similar. I started in a "V" like thing. left hand down pulling, right hand gastoning.  Quite hard first move. You definitely could start lower using a weird crimp undercling thing, but I kept hitting my battered shins so I opted out. Overall, the fracture boulder is a great place with quantity and quality.

ascents.comment: Definitely cool, but until the trails get more trafficked PLEASE wear pants and save your legs from the bush whack bleeding and rawness that made showering quite unpleasant. I went from "Clean Slate" to here and it was basically all shrubs; luckily you can get here much easier from the main road. I would have liked this more if my legs weren't stinging but that being said, this is a RAD feature.! The crux felt like the top out not the stemming section. Good stemming is rare tho so very worth it!

ascents.comment: The book was VERY generous with stars on climbs on this boulder that are not Rio's crack. I bet 98.3% of people who have done Rio's crack don't even realize there are climbs to the right. They are all forced, and well, not great. With out any visible chalk or sweet nothings from andyliu84 this felt hard. Basically a huge dead point to a hold above the lip from a slightly awkward position.

ascents.comment:
I think this may be V8, but then again, may be not. The start is VERY hard to find. It says start on two pockets, but there is only one obvious pocket. The other one is garbage. This is a rare line where starting lower IS ACTUALY easier. Literally. If you start where Sabersonic does a simple cross leads to jugs.  Very hard pull off the ground, thanks heel toe cam, leads to jugs. There is a big throw but its to a jug so... soft?
EDIT: Shriley I started on the miserable pockets. First move crux.

Got a solo session at rock creek today but third day on reeeeaaally is hard on the booty, by booty i mean body, you take a doodie with that? I'm a tired Grecian God that's for sure. Also Compression Session is really hard.  But back to the elephant, this climb is rad. Did the huge one arm swing dyno variant so yeah, I go big.

ascents.comment: The EPIC is over. 69 attempts.

ascents.comment: Wow. I've been intimidated by this for so gory darn long. People always said how soft this is and that frightened me! Could it really be that soft? What if I couldn't do it? Would people realize I'm actually weak? Thank God I did it today... this epic is over. Awesome line, only move i fell on was going to the pinch, that left slopey edge felt like shit. Same grade as the OG.

ascents.comment: I always wondered if this went before the new guide came out. Thanks Ian! Surprisingly fun with not so good landing. I used a finger lock and a toe cam, so you know its good. ascents.comment: My favorite part about this boulder is the great beer holder hueco on the rock behind. Shout out that. some good features, but either i didnt climb it well, or it doesnt climb that well.

ascents.comment: No fluttering hear on this? Just a note "Landing is pretty bad"? Wow V5 is hard these days. Seriously if anyone else does this they should probably upgrade. Its a basically a jump to a decent baseball sized hueco that you hold virtually one handed. Then the choss joins the party. I may be pooping on this but movement wise I though it was fun, i just wanted more points for it!

ascents.comment: Quite Unique, and deserving of your respect. Another one I remember watching Fanny (and Miguel) do back in the day. Pretty sure they campused the crux, and back then I couldn't even do the clapper. Always cool to run full circle on something you used to thing was impossible, only to realize its soft.

ascents.comment: Hardest line on the boulder. No question. A big round of applause is child's play. I cant believe Shirley didn't downgrade. Also Troy, did you really do this BEFORE Clapper? You cant flash if you had done the Clapper, sorry boy rules are rules. JK. Maybe you did it naked, I don't know. I also broke foot during my send burn. Not my foot mind you, the little piece of choss that is now a paper weight. Chaseypoo reaffirmed the grade, with a slightly worse foot about an inch to the right.

ascents.comment: Incredible. Great holds all the way up on a beautiful rock, fairly tall, with great and easy top out. Was planning on climbing at Lake Ramona this weekend but had a few too many Pure Project Quads and Black Tuesdays on Christmas. Spent all Saturday recovering: Binged an anime called BNA and started a great Korean show called Sweet Home. I was going to climb more today, but pomegranate tree pruning took like 6 hours, what a monster tree! It had over 800 fruits this season!

ascents.comment: Holy Poly there is a 'n' after the 'd'!? Who knew!? As a single boulder this is one of the better at Woodson, with a high quality V0 and two quality V7s (the second being the V4 'I shot the Sheriff'), its a fantastic little stop; plus its NEVER crowded. I unlocked a new school, long man beta to make this thing doper and probably easier. SUPER excited to come back and try the full sit, which definitely goes.

ascents.comment: Short but incredible. Take any gym baby climber here and they will love it. Plus gym babies hate heights so its a win win. Who doesn't love some good ol' fashioned power on jugs. Felt quite easy for V4, but my finger skin was hurting like the dickens today so maybe its the only climb that i didn't have to grate/slice my poor babies. Will definitely add this to the LR intro circuit when showing someone the area for the first time.

Whether it was just my finger skin or not, this felt harder than the OG. Not as good as the OG either, but a nice variation indeed.  The juggular feet make this quite enjoyable.

ascents.comment: Might be slightly gimmicky but when nature give you gimmicks, you  gobble them up! Nature is so amazing. The movement is unique, fun and pretty much forced. Its hard to even set a climb in the easier grade range this cool. It's in a beautiful location with good rock quality, what else could you ask for!?

ascents.comment: Its funny, this climb is also amazing, but when you compare it to the (Right) variation its slightly worse in each category. Still a MUST DO, but just funny that its incredible neighbor makes it feel less than it is. It is slightly less tall than the (Right) so that is maybe a perk. I am a happy man. You can see this climb / feature from the lake so that is something special too.

ascents.comment: Perfection. Utter bliss. This is easily one of my top 5 favorite climbs of ALL TIME. Aesthetics are 6 / 5: perfectly cleaved face with a striking sharp arete, and even has that gory darn diving board feature! Movement is 6 / 5: looks improbably but as you start climbing, it feels oh so natural. Rock quality is 5 / 5. You could come to LR for this alone and you would leave happy.

ascents.comment: I knew I was running on empty all day... but this is how I KNEW. know what I mean?  Fell at the top of a V3 because my body just completely gave out... took a super long break and managed to eek out the send but damn I'm destroyed. This is one of the most aesthetic climbs PERIOD. It doesn't even make sense how perfectly sculped the dike feature is.  Absolute must do.

ascents.comment:
Felt hard. Nice mantle into a few trust feet moves. My skin hurts so bad... climbing today may have been a bad idea.

Tried a rad line to the right of this trying to go directly up from a jug via some shallow pockets / mini crimps. Definitely goes but I will need more skin. Four of 'em to be exact.

ascents.comment: I don't even like crack, but this think is so epic and begs to be climbed. First move is rather painful but that's part of the appeal my dudes. I was honestly glad for something other that my tips to be screaming. This thing had awesome variety of movement of holds, but the steepness keeps it quite sustained. I ended up inverting to get one of my right hand jams in. It makes for a rather ludicrous but cool looking sequence.

ascents.comment: Wow. This thing seems like there are going to be a 100 betas, all of them good. Any climb that has perfect start holds at the base of a beautiful face is destined for greatness. A few razors on this one but ill spare you the finger skin complaints.

ascents.comment: An easier variation of "Wax On" Start sitting low on the north east corner of the boulder with left hand in the good seam and right hand on a low sloper. Pull on and join "Wax On".

ascents.comment: On the center of the East Face of the Grasshopper boulder.  Start on the super obvious jug and move right into a Gaston of your choice then  cross up to the awesome juggy pinch and top out, choosing the least chossy holds. Avoid most of the choss by moving right a tiny but.

ascents.comment: Don't get caught with your beard in the mailbox, my dudes! This GEM of a climb is on the backside of Leisure Lagoon boulder: start to the right of the tree (narrowly not dabbing) with right hand under the shelf in an underling and left hand on the lowest jug at the back of the shelf. All holds above the first shelf are OFF which forces some fun moves out right, with a crux big throw to the big corner. Top out WITHOUT using any holds above the corner.. why? Because I said so.

ascents.comment:
Scandinavia has the best idioms. Back side of Leisure Lagoon, right hand low under cling, left hand lowest jug in first shelf. Go straight up on good holds. 

Finally stuck the last undone moves of two more of my contrived Data + Picard variations. Thought today would be a goose egg, but found this surprising feature. Honestly Leisure Lagoon bolder is dop.  RPC may be facing some access issues as I have heard a few accounts of rangers saying No Climbing. Hopefully ACSD can help!

ascents.comment: I like the MP comment "Don't trash the rock". Lol. I don't think a run and jump is such an erosive event that we have to be worried about the rock crumbling after 3 people a year try this climb. Oh well, I do know their heart is in the right place. Run n Jumps could cause damage to the surrounding flora however so maybe that is worth worrying about. But then again no one does this. Anyway, this felt more like a waddle n jump. Not much run space and hard to aim your foot. Fun.

ascents.comment: I think you could even sit start this! Better than the run n jump IMO b/c its actually climbing, if that makes sense. Eileen joined me today and flashed 2 V0s and a V1 (V2 on MP but she said it couldn't be that hard lol). So many open undone projects at Hanging Gardens! The Van Gogh Project ~V8, Polyglot Project ~V8, Wonder Boy Project ~V9, and the Project Euler Project ~V8. Much excite to get back here.

ascents.comment: This is a harder intro into Little John's Crack, which means I got to run the gloriously tough V0 again. Could be V2? Probably depends on how low you start. Hilariously I saw some people from the top of the boulder who were trying to find little johns. I actually saw THREE groups of climbers today, all lost. The one group, a whole family, was looking for the Hanging Gardens.  I told them they only missed it by about a mile. The MP for the area can be a tad confusing for sure.

ascents.comment: Holy poly I was afraid of a good egg today! I mean this is a whopping 0 points but that's not the same as a true goose egg. I failed AGAIN on 'Final Round' and 'I Shot the Sheriff' and started to get seriously worried when I was 6 burns into this V0... the crack closes up completely at the top op this boulder and you need to do a delicate slab move almost 20' up. Quite good, takes a while to trust yourself, but once you do it again feels like V0.

ascents.comment: I was too tired to still be climbing. Was pumping out after any two moves. This climb is very un-Woodson-esque. Good holds and features, which make if feel pretty gym like. Kind of refreshing, and definite must do at the grade. Top is a jug.

ascents.comment: This thing is many much more mega than I expected. Its like 25' of climbing and the top out is like 20+ feet up over a bad landing.  If MP gave it a 'R' I probably would have already sought it out.  Height = Aesthetic. Amazingly I ran into people at this boulder! What? Its so obscure. Damn covid. But cool to see peeps exploring their local crags. Cruxy lip traverse low into amazing highball arete. It is easy up top but 10/10 would never put a V3 climber on this.

ascents.comment: OOOWheee! MSSGAS! Start as for Data and Picard but move diagonally up and left across the face. Another one I thought was crazy hard, but slowly found the easiest way to do each move, making it soft. Possibly too soft.  Could be V8... but until the Sandbox gets her to DG I'm taking it. Crux is sick, you get established on this sharp as hell left hand crimp, come over and match on something shitty then have to move out of it. Of the Federation starship my dudes!
