ascents.comment: Wow how did I miss this GEM.  On the back side of Garbage Compactor there is a good flat ledge about 1.5 feet off the ground. Use toe hook / bicycle shenanigans to establish then somehow navigate the lip without dabbing! An easier ~V3 variation uses a heel hook out right instead, but the best version starts with your body basically horizontal

ascents.comment: The third generation start to the OG Tea Earl Grey Hot. FAs are rad, if no one is ever going to climb them, who can validate your V Point integrity? Could be V8 but that first move is quite difficult for big fingers. Start Right hand on the obvious crimp in the middle of the face, and left hand very low on a small crimp. Hard left hand move into the side pull of Data and Picard gets you into the start of V6, one more move gets you into the OG. One more move for 3 Points!? Seems questionable

ascents.comment: This rock has definitely been pained over with rock colored paint to probably remove graffiti. Start on a pretty cool pinchy hold with crimps on either side, incredibly hard first move the way I did it (for V2 anyway, probably an easier beta I'm sure). After hitting that dope pinch it eases up significantly and simply follow up and right. Located above Garbage Compactor.

ascents.comment: If this was more accessible this would be a classic V4 at Woodson. Its a little short but the moves are fun, the holds are good, and most importantly its SOFT! I want to take a moment to give my mom a big shoutout for reaching her goal and running 11 miles today in just over 11 minutes per mile! If I can still run 11 miles at 63 I will be a happy camper. Mom you are amazing! I am so proud of you and happy to have been able to help.

ascents.comment: I've done it!! This is my 8A2K baby!!! 2,000 climbs logged on 8a. I wanna thank all my followers, my loving parents, sibling and friends, Petzle, Pokemon Go, Pure Project, and Tecnu. I couldn't have done it with out you all. Oh also Happy Birthday Chase!! And ill drink to that!

ascents.comment: This is the dangit hole of all dangit holes! You could fit and entire tiny house down here. Its a little scary because it kinda looks like with some more erosion all the surrounding boulders could shift / fall! Rather enjoyable but nothing to write home about. I did use feet first beta to get to the first jug on the right arete, so that was cool! Top is choss.

ascents.comment:
There may be more to explore at Woodson. There is so much rock out here there is no way someone has looked at every side of every rock, right!? Cant wait to get more poison oak!

Fun tallish flake system, pretty thin that its honestly scary pulling out not down. May warm up on this pair in the future.

ascents.comment: Failed on 4 / 4 of my projects but, I did this thing. Its to the right of "Final Round" about 15 feet, and starts about 10 ft off the ground above the classic oak tree. I really wanted a way to climb into the "start" holds, but it would be miserable and REALLY hard. If you shimmy between the rock and the oak tree you can reach the starting holds, paste a foot and pull on. A couple sweet crimps lead into "Ride the wave". Start on the good left-ish facing edge and a worse but opposing hold.

ascents.comment: Flash FA! The classic combo! Located on the north corner of the Smurf /Gargamel boulder. Cool arete feature into a mantle encounter over a less than ideal landing.  Scare factor certainty adds to the mantle difficulty but this rig packs some good movement. Start on the obvious blocky jug thing work left and up to a big bump to a good hold, then a jug, then get your mantle hat on! Azrael is Gargamels cat. Nice kitty!

ascents.comment: Thanks Kody for establishing this amazing gem! A little spicy, but once you know how to utilize the back rock its quite safe. Perfect rock with cool holds up and incredible face. Was quite bewildered that I bagged. Feels hard because the crux is rather low probability and rather high up. One of the best V8s on the mountain which says a lot because black is known for those. Much more attractive then the crusty wizard of whom it is named.

ascents.comment: Its actually called "Unnamed Mantle" but as you all now I don't dig that. The yellow mantle on the rock behind "Gimme Some". That Traeblood got me thinking about pancakes. Who needs pads when a napkin will do. Rather impressed I flashed because everything felt insecure, but i had to impress Kody! As mantles go, its good.

ascents.comment: Wow whee! Look's like it should be rather easy, but requires a ton of technique! Truly technical problems like this are rare, and it was very enjoyable working it out. I actually tried this back when I first saw "Dont tell anyone" but could't bag, and Kody finished her up a few weeks ago; good job adding another great line! Still sweet as FA's to be had at black!

ascents.comment: Fun one mover! Some days I couldn't even pull off the ground, but the post rain cold friction and productive day at work just lifted me right up. Start left hand on the surprisingly hard-to-rip-off "tongue", and right hand on an opposing crimp off to the right. The feet are pretty bad.  If you train pinching wood 4x4 s this probably feels cakey. Make a big ol' move up to the jug and top out!

ascents.comment: Might be V8, especially if the crux foot continues to crumble. It only broke on me like 7 times. One time I was high in the mantle placing my right foot next to my right hand when I got crimson chinned. It was a good one! That being said once I micro-ed the holds it felt rather repeatable.  Start in the scoop to the left of Moon as my Wittness, get a high left foot, grab a micro sharp crystally bastard and mantle that shit. Once mantelled you still have a tenuous step up! Fun! Project 10 on MP.

Start right hand on the obvious ear crimp, that may rip off one day. Left hand anywhere on the opposing sloper feature. Surprisingly hard slaps get you up. I am curios if a lower start goes to both this and "polyglot"! Food for drewbie when he comes.

I cant wait to FA and area called Alex Patterson and name every single climb Alex Patterson. Its gonna be good.

ascents.comment: Quite nice! Hard to imagine this being V9 when its basically a shortcut of Sabres of Paradise. Heel hook beta for Sabersonic crux is much better in both enjoyment and ease. I have now done everything on this boulder! I guess I could do Super Jack of Swords if I ever end up back here. Big shoutout the one and only human waffle for surpassing he limits and going beyond plus ultra to bag Alex Patterson!

ascents.comment: Holy cow my Goose Egg day was saved by a flying man in a loincloth! By that I mean Lisa told me this was a climb and I did it. Rad feature. Would world class if the feature continued for more than like 1 move. Lisa with an inspiring day sending Rios quickly in some beautiful and softly falling wet snow then soft second going Water Hazard right.

ascents.comment:
That's two votes in favor!! Felt destroyed but Chooch with the inspiring Hamtaro send gave me the chutzpah I needed to pull this. Send train baby! Technically speaking there was a "dab" or two during the no hands rest =P, but well, they were good dabs. That no hands rest kind of makes the first 20 feet of the traverse pointless.... I guessI'm a sport climber now!
Also need to should out Dan and Josh for making their first Bishop trip! Proud of you guys are sticking with climbing!

ascents.comment: Nothing quite like climbing all week and wait until the morning of the last day of your trip to try your proj lol. I'm bad at resting so my body was devastated.  Thanks Chooch for both the psyche and the tp, both were vital to my sending. Honestly very cool moves, the ice caves are just an awesome formation. Its amazing how bad the crux right foot feels until one burn and then it just never blows again. Thanks for an unforgettable week, Chooch!

ascents.comment: First face you see when walking into the Hanging Gardens and despite is obvious beauty it went undone for so long! Vertical face with just enough holds to be possible. Such interesting delicate movement which requires so pretty serious micro . Might be easier that V9 but it is hard to grade a puzzle.  So proud! Definitely one of my better FAs and definitely my best addition to Woodson so far. There is potential for a Sit as well! Nothin like a Pure Project Quad to celebrate, Kody you missed out!

ascents.comment: I hope this has been done before me, but its not on MP even though it is such a glorious line! Slot yourself in between bowser and Waluigi and ride the most obvious crack feature up and left for a good 20 feet of climbing before a perfect mantel. Watch out for oncoming traffic! Slightly contrived but hey, we are boulders for a reason! My Mario Kart references no longer make sense because I corrected the name to "The Patio" to be consistent with older guide books of woodson!

ascents.comment: Wow. Crimpers and hang board masters all, come see this new one move wonder! Start with left on a good slightly right facing crimp in the low seam below "The Patio" and right hand another hold in the seam. Pull on and do a surprisingly hard campus into the jug side pull ~8 feet into "The Patio". Then finish her up. Reminiscent of the classic shortcut on the N64 track. Could definitely start one set of holds further left but it felt fucked. Would be cool though!

ascents.comment: Was tossing a lot of potential names around for this one but the water has finally settled, just keep swimming. Thanks Dory! Crazy friction dependent. Basically compressing up a full extension rounded feature on frustrating feet. Amazing weekend with Lisa! Only stayed out here till just after midnight. I love that we sat at the blasted boulder to do Duolingo together; don't lose those streaks! Also Lisa you throw  a mean left elbow hook!

ascents.comment: This is named in honor of a fabulous weekend with Lisa. How many people stay out bouldering past midnight? Of those how many take a Duolingo break at 11:50 to not lose their streaks!? Lol! So awesome to share this quirk with Lisa. We successfully saved our streaks both at Woodson yesterday and today at RPC. It t'was an unforgettable record setting weekend indeed. Should have let Lisa try this first since she cruised it! I've been trying it for a few sessions and it makes a great addition to RPC

ascents.comment: That's another for hat fall off bingo! Woot! Holy poly this thing became a Homer lengthed epic for me. So hard. Why can I flail on it the day before, then come back more tired, hotter temps, wetter tips and having forgot to morning poop and send M Soft First Go? Classic climbing. Oh, that's right I brought a better send beer this time! Thanks Lisa and Kim for a great trip and amazing support on this saga.

ascents.comment: Wow redemption after missing my chance to send before last season ended. My skin is just the worst so I was honestly worried it might not go today. Second or so burn of the day I held it together and took it to the top, topping out WAY better than Shirley. Seriously that guy looked real bad up there.  Only crumbled the first overzealous gaston a few times with my foot: luckily its big enough to still be good after loosing like a millimeter or two. A tad soft, but clearly harder than overzealous.

ascents.comment: Miracles happen every day boys and girls. So do shitty things. Remember that. Saw someone just dyno this climb from pretty low on the inter webs and decided to try the same. Surprised myself with a clean snag on the ~second burn of the day. Great temps, great friend and great beer always help. Close on the sit but it eats your fingers. I got to the dyno once from the ground, but was in utter disbelief that I stuck the dyno from such shitty feet. Next time! PSF for Lisa on The Fluke!

ascents.comment: A aesthetic face truth be told, but tis a silly place... lets not go to Camelot. Stack a few pads then pull one decent fingery face move to easier top. But yes certainly should not be in the same league as Osama...

ascents.comment: Very soft... honestly the V4 feels the same difficulty. But what would I know I'm not a doctor.  Cool variation through, rosed under for the match out right.

ascents.comment: Felt awful at morning yoga, then was pleasantly surprised by a closed Looney Bean kitchen forcing us to get delicious food across the street at an amazing Cuban food truck! Ate too much deliciousness, and spice and had to walk it off by showing Lisa Checkerboard. After a pre send poop, and a pre send fail, I finally managed to bag. Way easier than Fall Guy, harder than Fly Boy, maybe low end but felt V9. Took a full value swing latching the top!

ascents.comment: Pretty sure I tried this a long time ago with Jess Chen and may have made an absolute fool of myself in more ways than one. My sincerest apologies.  I had the craziest Deja Vu on the top out, and had to search my logs to verify if id actually done this or now. I vaguely remember climbing this in a dream... what a shitty climb to dream about. But it was fun today.

ascents.comment: Miracle send honestly. Easy bonus V points once you have the top dialed. Those razor blades are miserable but they don't add to much difficulty. Why could I not put this together the other night when I still had skin and fuel in the tank? A quad, a hazy, a booch and a smoothie style ale was apparently all the inspiration I needed. Shoutout Waffleman for cruising Overzealous and punching The Fluke and winning the bleed on the pads bet. Had a genuine presend flail and Chooch got the whole thing!

ascents.comment: (direct) - Just as hard as the OG but a cool tenuous variation.
ascents.notes: (direct) - Just as hard as the OG but a cool tenuous variation.

ascents.comment: Thought this would be my best chance at a V9 flash, so much Gregor style it has! Might have been feasible if it wasn't my 5th day on,  but when in Rome, climb like you will never climb again. Harder than it looks, especially working though the right hand slopers. Found slightly different betas than what the interwebbers use, and felt nice to me. Awesome climb. Thanks Shirley for locating, Chooch for support+vid and Nach for being a trooper through the over hiking and bush wacking!

ascents.comment: (PRNF - Pending Real Name Found). This is the sit start of the face on the back side of the Mad Hatter. Anyone who comes to this boulder has probably warmed up on this thing before doing the Mad Hatter. The stand is maybe a V2 but the sit adds a kinda cool, kinda really awkward but entertaining start. Start sitting on the south side of the boulder on a pretty obvious corner edge. Pull in to the cool side pull system, into some good edges and ultimately the arete to top.

ascents.comment: Was hoping to pull another miracle and send Lawnmower man today but those moves are too powerful and I could feel the starts of tendonitis hell. 6th day on is too much. Lisa did cruise French Press with style and crucial swiftness for us to make her flight in time! Anyway, is this climb effing hard or is it just me? Climbs super well, but I had a large DP to the lip which was mildly scary. Days climbed metric baby!

ascents.comment: My knees were very happy to have the 4 pads for this. Dyno from the left facing Crimp Jug (to the left of the "river") straight to the top. You can sit start way down on the underclings if you want and off route the entire river, but the beginning is such choss you might just pull a 75 pound piece of rock on top of yourself. Once that choss falls off, it may be a cool sit. Wanted to give this V8 but damn I still cant to "Final Round" so it cant be.

ascents.comment: Tested out the new 2x Big Organic, 2x Small Organics and 1x Send Blubber today. The watermelon family was happy to have an outing together. On trails without anything above me my new set up is casual. The last steep bush cave part into hanging gardens was tough. That being said stoked to keep improving my fitness! This climb starts on the same jugs as The River Tirgis but doesn't use any holds to the right of the "river". May be reachy, but cool last move.

ascents.comment: Adam Burch Memorial Slab Problem. Many SEASONED slab masters have done this and I've seen someone do this, but I still think there is a chance that its an FA. I do have big BALLz. Anyway, this thing is contrived and terrifying, but you get to use two HONKER knobs. I bet you like that Adam. There is a 10`+ fall to your right w/ bad landing as you smear on shit to stab out to the foot knob. To the right of Cheap Thrills, go right, up is not allowed. Also 4 full pts go staight to the final honker.

ascents.comment: This is a tall boulder with a bad landing. Fitness such as mine is mucho importanto if doing this alone 4x pads is a minimum. There was/is alot of shit rock low, but cleaning up nice-ish. Also, trying to not dab on the "crack" side pulls is tough. That left chunk is def not on, good thing a boulderer FA'ed this. Start on rad left facing holds in a dang-it location and movement is only saved by a glorious to hook out right. AMAZING rock over to top out ~25 feet on SEASONED slab.
